Sheffield — a living model

A full-screen, pan-and-zoom 3D model of Sheffield that fuses Environment Agency
LIDAR terrain with OpenStreetMap buildings and a handful of live, primary-source
open-data feeds. Understated, a little SimCity: the whole city is drawn as 1px
hairlines on black — terrain as a lifted wire grid, buildings as edge wireframes,
feeds as billboarded markers — straight from open data onto the GPU. Trams glide
around the real network; live buses ride the real roads.

Live at ltrg.co.uk/sheffield


Running it

    make          fetch every feed into data/  (gitignored — not committed)
    make serve    static server -> http://localhost:8000
    make lidar    stream EA LIDAR into data/terrain.bin  (no key, ~5 min;
                  without it the terrain is silently flat)

No build step, no framework, no map library, no CDN. The frontend is plain ES
modules driving a custom WebGPU renderer; the backend is dependency-light Python
run under uv (which just pins the interpreter — zero pip deps). The two sides are
decoupled by files: the fetchers write data/ (compact geojson, or a packed .bin
for the heavy layers — buildings, gas pipes, terrain), the frontend polls them.
That file contract is the whole interface, with one exception: live buses are
pulled straight from bustimes.org in the browser (a CORS-enabled, no-key feed),
so they're real-time with no backend, no key and no proxy.

Optional key (cp .env.example .env):
    OPENROUTER_API_KEY / ANTHROPIC_API_KEY   LLM geocoding of news/reddit/tribune
                  headlines (falls back to a built-in gazetteer without either)


What you're looking at

    Terrain        Sheffield's real hills from EA LIDAR, draped as a wire grid.
    Buildings      OSM footprints + heights extruded into see-through wireframes,
                   clickable for their OSM tags.
    Trams          every Supertram line along real OSM geometry. Supertram has no
                   live vehicle feed, so trams are estimated from the published
                   timetable — real headways and speeds within service hours.
                   Honest and deterministic; the status bar says so.
    Live buses     bustimes.org (DfT BODS SIRI-VM), interpolated along the roads.
    Rivers         EA level gauges, latest reading + flood ratio.
    Air quality    Sheffield City Council's real air-quality monitors.
    Utilities      Cadent gas mains/services (tinted by install age) + sites, and
                   OSM trunk pipelines (gas NTS backbone, water, fuel), buried at
                   their inferred depth of cover.
    Open data      crime, council faults, CCTV, trees, development sites, wards,
                   the Clean Air Zone, and geolocated news / r/sheffield / Tribune
                   — each a toggle.


Data sources — all primary, no aggregators

    Trams, buildings, roads, trees   OpenStreetMap (Overpass)          no key
    Street crime                     data.police.uk (Home Office)      no key
    CCTV, faults, wards, CAZ, sites  Sheffield City Council ArcGIS     no key
    Live bus positions               bustimes.org (DfT BODS SIRI-VM)   no key
    River levels                     EA flood-monitoring               no key
    Air quality                      Sheffield City Council monitors   no key
    Gas network                      Cadent (opendatasoft)             key
    Trunk pipelines                  OpenStreetMap (Overpass)          no key
    News / r/sheffield / Tribune     RSS + LLM geocoding               optional
    Terrain                          EA LIDAR Composite DTM 1m (WCS)   no key


Deployment

GitHub Pages, no server. The frontend lives in git; the data lives in the
"latest-data" GitHub Release (a data.zip of all of data/, geojson + packed .bin).
A deploy workflow assembles frontend + data into the Pages site; a daily sync
workflow re-fetches the feeds that change, refreshes the release, and redeploys.


Layout

    index.html  app.js  config.js  style.css   frontend
    gpu.js  proj.js                             webgpu device/pipelines, projection,
                                                camera, terrain
    fetchers/                                   one robust script per data source
    data/                                       geojson + packed .bin the fetchers
                                                write (gitignored)
    Makefile  pyproject.toml  .env.example      uv-run data orchestration

config.js is the only place to tune: camera, the rendered bbox, terrain params,
the feed poll intervals, and the layer toggles. Touch it before the JS.
